{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649809"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:08:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:08:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18381"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18381"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.04,0.71,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79421"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11099"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64743"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79421"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a biomechanical function of the plantar fascia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facilitates ankle dorsiflexion","Enhances hip abduction","Maintains the arch of the foot","Prevents knee hyperextension","Supports the lateral collateral ligament"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe plantar fascia is a thick band of connective tissue that runs along the bottom of the foot from the heel to the toes. Its primary biomechanical function is to \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintain the arch of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E, providing support and stability during weight-bearing activities. This function is crucial for absorbing shock and distributing weight evenly across the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitating ankle dorsiflexion\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of the plantar fascia. This movement is primarily controlled by the muscles in the anterior compartment of the leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe plantar fascia does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent knee hyperextension\u003C/strong\u003E. This function is primarily managed by the ligaments and muscles around the knee joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the plantar fascia supports the foot, it does not directly \u003Cstrong\u003Esupport the lateral collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, which is located in the knee and provides lateral stability to the joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe plantar fascia does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhance hip abduction\u003C/strong\u003E. This movement is controlled by the muscles around the hip joint, such as the gluteus medius and minimus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The plantar fascia plays a crucial role in maintaining the arch of the foot.","It assists in absorbing shock and distributing weight during walking and running.","The plantar fascia contributes to the windlass mechanism, which stabilises the foot during propulsion."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64743"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18381"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64743"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T14:07:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T14:08:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11099"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79421"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap